  <h2>Sources</h2>
  <p>Every quotation on this site is drawn from a published, verifiable source. The lists below are the answer sites, curated readers, and classical works the topic pages most often cite. They were chosen because their answering scholars and editors operate within the four-madhhab Sunnī framework and the classical creedal schools (Ashʿarī, Māturīdī, Atharī) — the scholarly mainstream of Sunnī Islam.</p>

  <h3>Q&amp;A sites</h3>

  <p><strong>SeekersGuidance.</strong> <a href="https://seekersguidance.org/" rel="noopener external">seekersguidance.org</a> — Founded by Shaykh Faraz Rabbani, with a roster of scholars across all four madhāhib and the recognized creedal schools.</p>

  <p><strong>IslamQA.org.</strong> <a href="https://islamqa.org/" rel="noopener external">islamqa.org</a> — The traditional Ḥanafī Q&amp;A site overseen by an affiliated network of dār al-iftāʾ institutions. (Distinct from the unrelated islamqa.info, which is Salafī-aligned.)</p>

  <p><strong>Ask Imam.</strong> <a href="https://askimam.org/" rel="noopener external">askimam.org</a> — Madrasah-In'aamiyyah's Q&amp;A platform, led by Mufti Ebrahim Desai (raḥimahullāh). Ḥanafī, traditionalist.</p>

  <p><strong>hadithanswers.com.</strong> <a href="https://hadithanswers.com/" rel="noopener external">hadithanswers.com</a> — Dedicated to ḥadīth verification and grading from the classical Sunnī tradition; useful for sourcing the chains of reports that come up in disputes.</p>

  <h3>Curated readers and refutation sites</h3>

  <p>These sites do not produce original fatwa but compile classical Sunnī material — verbatim quotations from al-Nawawī, al-Suyūṭī, al-Subkī, al-Haytamī, al-Bayhaqī, and others — organised topic-by-topic. They are useful entry points for finding the classical sources that lie behind the contemporary debates.</p>

  <p><strong>Wahhabis Refuted.</strong> <a href="https://wahhabisrefuted.wordpress.com/" rel="noopener external">wahhabisrefuted.wordpress.com</a> — A topic-organised reader of classical Sunnī rebuttals to specific Salafī claims, drawing on Ibn ʿAsākir, al-Subkī, al-Haytamī, and contemporary scholars in the same line.</p>

  <p><strong>The Usuli.</strong> <a href="https://www.theusuli.com/" rel="noopener external">theusuli.com</a> — Essays and articles by Sh. Samir Hussain on traditional Sunnī uṣūl, fiqh, ʿaqīdah, and the historical and intellectual relationship of contemporary Salafism to the four-madhhab tradition.</p>

  <p><strong>Marifah.</strong> <a href="https://www.marifah.net/" rel="noopener external">marifah.net</a> — A reader-style archive of traditional Sunnī articles, translations, and biographical material across the four madhāhib and the Ashʿarī / Māturīdī schools.</p>

  <p><strong>masud.co.uk.</strong> <a href="http://www.masud.co.uk/" rel="noopener external">masud.co.uk</a> — The personal website of Br. Masud Khan, hosting articles, fatwa-style answers, and translated works by Sh. Nuh Keller (translator of the <em>Reliance of the Traveller</em>) and other traditional Sunnī scholars writing in English.</p>

  <h3>Classical works cited on this site</h3>

  <p>Where the topic pages cite a classical work directly — without an intermediate URL — these are the editions and authors whose works the citations refer to. They are listed here so a reader can locate them through any major Islamic library or printed edition.</p>

  <p>Imam Abū Jaʿfar al-Ṭaḥāwī (d. 321 AH), <em>al-ʿAqīda al-Ṭaḥāwiyya</em> — the most widely-accepted Sunnī creedal text across the Atharī, Ashʿarī, and Māturīdī schools.</p>

  <p>Ḥāfiẓ Ibn ʿAsākir (d. 571 AH), <em>Tabyīn Kadhib al-Muftarī fī mā Nusiba ilā al-Imām al-Ashʿarī</em> — the foundational refutation of the claim that Imam al-Ashʿarī recanted his Ashʿarī positions.</p>

  <p>Imam al-Nawawī (d. 676 AH), <em>al-Adhkār</em> and <em>al-Majmūʿ Sharḥ al-Muhadhdhab</em> — standard classical Shāfiʿī references on devotional practice (dhikr, ziyāra, tawassul) and fiqh.</p>

  <p>Imam Jalāl al-Dīn al-Suyūṭī (d. 911 AH), <em>Ḥusn al-Maqṣid fī ʿAmal al-Mawlid</em> — the standard classical Sunnī treatise classifying the Mawlid as a praiseworthy innovation (<em>bidʿa ḥasana</em>).</p>

  <p>Imam Taqī al-Dīn al-Subkī (d. 756 AH), <em>Shifāʾ al-Saqām fī Ziyārat Khayr al-Anām</em> and <em>al-Sayf al-Ṣaqīl</em> — classical Shāfiʿī defenses of tawassul, ziyāra, and the Ashʿarī ʿaqīdah, written specifically against the Ibn Taymiyya line.</p>

  <p>Ibn Ḥajar al-Haytamī (d. 974 AH), <em>al-Jawhar al-Munaẓẓam</em> and <em>al-Fatāwā al-Ḥadīthiyya</em> — late-Mamlūk Shāfiʿī fatwa collections on the same topics.</p>

  <p>Imam Aḥmad ibn Zaynī Daḥlān (d. 1304 AH), <em>Fitnat al-Wahhābiyya</em> — one of the earliest formal refutations of the 18th-century Najdī movement, written by the Mufti of Mecca.</p>

  <p>Imam Yūsuf al-Nabhānī (d. 1932 CE), <em>Shawāhid al-Ḥaqq fī al-Istighātha bi-Sayyid al-Khalq</em> — a comprehensive late-Ottoman defense of istighātha and tawassul through the Prophet ﷺ.</p>

  <h3>What's not on this list</h3>

  <p>Salafī-aligned sites (such as islamqa.info, binbaz.org.sa, sahab.net, or any of the major English-language Salafī publishing houses) are not listed here. They are cited on the topic pages where the Salafī position is being presented and engaged — but they are not part of this site's source whitelist for affirmative classical Sunnī teaching, since their methodology and creed depart from the four-madhhab Ashʿarī / Māturīdī / Atharī tradition this site frames itself within.</p>
